import LabLayout from '../../layouts/LabLayout.astro';
---

<LabLayout title="Lab 6: IoT and SPI" labNum={6} githubUrl="https://github.com/juliacygong/E155/tree/main/lab06/src">
  <section>
    <h2>Introduction</h2>
    <p>
      In this lab, I designed and built a simple IoT device, wrote C libraries to implement SPI on the MCU
      and interface with a temperature sensor, interfaced with an ESP8266 module over UART, and built an HTML
      page to control an LED and temperature sensor. The webpage lets users select output resolution for the
      temperature sensor and displays the reading. Selecting a resolution triggers the MCU to send the
      appropriate write and read commands over SPI.
    </p>

    <h2>MCU Design and Testing Methodology</h2>
    <p>
      The MCU uses UART to communicate with the ESP8266 and SPI to communicate with the temperature sensor.
      The ESP8266 creates a WiFi access point and serves the webpage from the MCU. Connecting to the network
      and navigating to <code>http://192.168.4.1/</code> displays the page.
    </p>
    <p>
      A 125000 baud UART connection links the MCU and ESP8266. The MCU sends an HTML file; the ESP8266 updates
      the page and forwards user requests back to the MCU.
    </p>
    <p>
      Temperature resolution commands from the user determine the SPI write/read commands. The number of
      resolution bits is written to the sensor register, then 2 bytes are read: MSB (with sign bit) and LSB.
      Temperature is computed as: <code>Temp = MSB + LSB / 256.0</code>
    </p>

    <h2>Technical Documentation</h2>
    <p>
      Source code in <a href="https://github.com/juliacygong/E155/tree/main/lab06/src" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>:
      <code>main.c</code>, SPI configuration, temperature sensor configuration, and external libraries.
    </p>

    <h3>Schematic</h3>
    <figure>
      <img src="/images/labs/lab6/lab6schematic.jpeg" alt="Schematic" />
      <figcaption>Figure 1: MCU connections to LED, ESP8266, and temperature sensor.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>Results and Discussion</h2>
    <p>
      The system correctly interfaces with the LED and temperature sensor through the HTML webpage. The
      display shows temperature readings getting more precise as resolution increases.
    </p>
    <iframe src="https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Vby-pSSeZ3AxWrfpYfxx-3frQddxamIw/preview"
            width="740" height="480" allow="autoplay"></iframe>

    <h3>SPI Logic Analyzer Trace</h3>
    <figure>
      <img src="/images/labs/lab6/lab6scope.JPG" alt="Logic analyzer trace" />
      <figcaption>Figure 2: Logic analyzer trace for an 8-bit temperature sensor command.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>Signals: D0 = CS, D1 = CLK, D2 = MISO, D3 = MOSI.</p>
    <p>
      After CS goes high: MCU sends <code>0x80</code> (write config register address), then <code>0xE0</code>
      (8-bit resolution). Second CS: MCU sends <code>0x02</code> to read MSB, <code>0x00</code> filler →
      receives <code>0x17</code>. Then <code>0x01</code> to read LSB → receives <code>0x00</code>.
      Decoded temperature: 23 + 0/256 = <strong>23°C</strong>.
    </p>

    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>
      Successfully built a system interfacing a temperature sensor over SPI and an ESP8266 over UART to
      create a webpage that controls and displays temperature data. This lab took 12 hours.
    </p>

    <h2>AI Prototype Summary</h2>
    <p>Two prompts tested:</p>
    <ol style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0.75rem 1.5rem; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><em>Create an HTML page to show temperature, control an LED, and change precision.</em> → ChatGPT produced a more aesthetically polished page than mine (better colors, font sizes).</li>
      <li><em>Write a C function to carry out a SPI transaction to retrieve a temperature reading from a DS1722 on the STM32L432KC.</em> → Code was incorrect: wrong SPI phase and improper temperature calculation.</li>
    </ol>
  </section>
